# addEventListener ğŸ‘‚

The modern standard way to handle events. It attaches an event handler to the specified element without overwriting existing event handlers.

```javascript
element.addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Hello World!");
});
```
- Syntax: `element.addEventListener(event, function, useCapture);`

# removeEventListener ğŸ›‘

To remove an event handler, you must use a named function (not an anonymous one) during addition.

```javascript
function myFunction() {
  alert("Clicked!");
}

// Add
btn.addEventListener("click", myFunction);

// Remove
btn.removeEventListener("click", myFunction);
```

# Event Object ğŸ“¦

When an event occurs, the browser passes an **event object** to the handler function. It contains details about the event.

```javascript
btn.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
  console.log(event.target); // The element clicked
  console.log(event.type);   // "click"
});
```

# preventDefault() âœ‹

Stops the default action of an element from happening.

Example: Prevent a link from opening the URL.

```javascript
document.querySelector("a").addEventListener("click", function(event) {
  event.preventDefault();
});
```

# Event Delegation ğŸ‘®

Instead of attaching listeners to every child, attach one to the parent.

Useful for dynamically added elements.

```javascript
// List with many items
document.getElementById("myList").addEventListener("click", function(e) {
  if (e.target.tagName === "LI") {
    alert("List item clicked!");
  }
});
```

